NY Senate again passes utility legislation package . The New York State Senate has again passed three pieces of legislation backers expect will significantly reduce electric utility rates . The package does not have a sponsor in the Assembly , according to Charles Carrier , a spokesman for Speaker Sheldon Silver . Noting " parts of New York have the highest energy costs in the country , " Senate Majority Leader Joseph L . Bruno said : " The bills we passed ( Wednesday ) will reduce those costs and guarantee that savings will be passed along to ratepayers in the form of lower monthly utility bills . " A spokesman for the majority said Friday the " only significant change " in the legislative package from the version passed by the Senate last year is " minor changes to assure ( resulting ) savings go to rate payers . " The Senate passed a bill that would phase - out the Gross Receipts Tax on energy and telecommunications . It would freeze the tax in 1997 , then phase it out over the next four years . A statement released by the Senate majority said phasing - out the GRT would save ratepayers $ 710 million a year when fully implemented . The statement included the following utility - by - utility estimate of the portion of each revenue dollar going to taxes , saying it was provided by the Energy Association of New York . Electric Utility State Local State & Local Consolidated Edison $ 0 . 087 $ 0 . 148 $ 0 . 236 Long Island Lighting 0 . 079 0 . 143 0 . 222 Orange and Rockland 0 . 074 0 . 112 0 . 185 Niagara Mohawk 0 . 064 0 . 099 0 . 162 Central Hudson 0 . 066 0 . 087 0 . 153 Rochester Gas 0 . 066 0 . 083 0 . 149 N . Y . State Electric 0 . 062 0 . 073 0 . 135 AVERAGE 0 . 071 0 . 106 0 . 177It said the Senate approved the " Electric Ratepayer Relief Act " , also known as the " Securitization " bill , which would establish a financing mechanism for the state ' s electric utilities to obtain lower cost financing which will result in lower electric rates . Also passed was the " Power For Prosperity " bill designed to make 400 megawatts of low cost power available for economic development . The power , provided jointly by the state Power Authority and investor - owned utilities , would be made available to businesses for the purpose of job retention . ( ( - - New York Newsdesk 212 - 859 - 1610 . ) ) 
